title: For Sale:  Nepalese Francotte Martini Henry rifle (not to shoot)
postcontent:
Have a Francotte martini rifle made in Nepal. It's mostly a wall hanger but if you really wanted to it can be fired. If you chose to do so that's at your own risk. The gun is pretty lose and would have head space issues. But you could hang it over your fireplace as a show n tell piece that "could" be loaded and shot 

Bought this knowing that the chances of this being a shooter were slim. It seems unsafe to shoot and the reading I've done suggests the same. That being said its not "unable" to shoot, but there are a few things that need to be replaced. I'll get to that later. I started with getting the action open. The firing pin was broken and stuck in the forward position. This was keep in the breach from opening. Once I got that taken care of the guts were able to fall out for service. So far all the parts that have been numbered match. Numbered parts I've found are the barrel bands, barrel, lever, trigger / breach block frame, breach block and the fore end. Matching numbers is not helping the mechanics though as the fit is pretty lose. 

Now there are 3 missing parts. The first is the screw that holds the action together in front of the trigger guard. The second is the firing pin. I still have the broken one,  it's pulled out so the action doesn't lock up again. And the last part is a captive screw on the inside. This one dose not appear to affect function, just there to keep the sear pin from falling out of the frame when removed from the receiver. The gun could be dry fired if the takedown screw and firing pin were replaced.  

Selling as a parts gun, wall hanger or just as an example of the Martini Henry that can be handled. The thing is fun to point and drop the breach on. All the internals are able to move freely. The stock is lose, but that's because I don't have a screw driver long enough to tighten it. If you replaced the missing parts maybe it could be used to touch off low powered blanks on the 4 of July or something.

title: For Sale:  Para Ordnance .45 ACP P1445 Expert 15 shot 2 Magazines Fiber Optic Front Sight Para USA 96765 45 Automatic
postcontent: Seller Stock #: HG96765 Para Ordnance pistols began showing up here in West Tennessee in the late 1980s. Before they came, there was no such thing as a quality .45 Auto that would hold anywhere near 15 rounds of ammunition. Para pistols have earned their stripes with our local clientele. They look good, they’re well constructed and well finished, and most important, they’re reliable and accurate. Here is Para’s P1445, Expert variant. Manufacturer is Para USA of Charlotte, NC, formerly of Scarborough, Ontario. Photo specimen is one of fewer than 2 dozen pieces of sales representatives’ show guns. Surface detractions are negligible, no more than any brand new Para in a gun store that gets put on display: slide contact marking on the hammer face edge, bushing contact streaking on the barrel surface, and insertion and ejection marking on the magazines. This pistol and its mates come to us from Para’s distribution channels; it has never been transferred. We rate it as Near Mint in Box. Construction is steel slide, frame, and stainless barrel, with Nitride black steel bushing, spring cap, sights, slide stop, main safety, grip safety, hammer, and magazine release. Mainspring housing, grips and magazine floorplates are black polymer. Trigger is .240 serrated face black alloy skeleton with overtravel adjustment, with matching skeleton serrated steel Commander type hammer. Barrel is match grade stainless, and so marked, with six groove 1:16 Left Hand Twist rifling. Sights are dovetailed into the slide, black blade raised type rear, with steel housed green high visibility fiber optic front. Photo specimen gauged at 4 1/4 pounds trigger pull with minimal felt creep. Safety system is series 80 type, with firing pin safety in addition to extended steel main safety and beaver grip safeties. Magazine release and main safety are for right handed shooters; this pistol is not southpaw friendly. Slide stop is standard width serrated, and magazine release is extension steel serrated. Mainspring housing is flat C type serrated black polymer. Grip frame is 8 groove serrated front, with para factory black polymer checkered grips secured with blue steel Torx head screws. Weight empty is 40 ounces, with center of gravity at the trigger. Magazines are matte blue steel 14 shot factory Para with black polymer floorplates and Novak type cartridge followers. Magazines were manufactured by Mec-Gar for Para. Each pistol comes in its factory Gray Box with cable lock and instruction manual that includes Para’s statement of warranty. Replacement pricing on similar pistols from other manufacturers approaches $1500 per unit many times. title: For Sale/Trade:  Rock Island Armory 2011 9mm
postcontent:
RIA changed the name on this pistol, but the specs are the same. https://us.armscor.com/products/tac-ultra-fs-hc-9mm

This pistol is a doublestack 9mm with a light rail on the full dust cover. Has a total of 3 (factory only sends 1) 17 round magazines. If you want more magazines, use the Mec-Gar mags. Has adjustable 2 white dot rear sight, and red fiber optic front, magwell, ambidextrous safety, beavertail safety, G10 grips, and flat mainspring housing. Great 3 gun pistol!

Although this is the 9mm version, my understanding is that you can buy the 22 TCM barrel, and use the normal 9mm mags, if you want to run the 22 TCM. That round is pretty amazing if you haven't checked it out. 40 gr bullet going over 2000 fps out of a pistol.

These double stack 9mm's have gotten popular for 3 gun, and it is no wonder why. It is a great pistol, but I just don't have a need for it anymore. $700 FTF until Governor Brown signs off forbidding it.
